This paper is primarily focused on software maintenance and bug localization, which falls under the software engineering (cs.SE) category. The paper extensively studies the performance of state-of-the-art bug localization tools, which heavily rely on information retrieval (IR) techniques, indicating a possible fit for the information retrieval (cs.IR) category. The proposed approach also involves supervised learning, specifically gradient boosting, which falls under the machine learning (cs.LG) category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of various features and token types, which could be relevant to the programming languages (cs.PL) category. Finally, the paper deals with the analysis of unstructured data, which could be relevant to the software development (cs.SD) category.
